We will calculate each metric as follows:

1. ROE (Return on Equity):
• Use the net profit from the income statement and the average owner’s equity (average of beginning and ending equity).
  Beginning Owner’s Equity = 13,000,000.00 
  Ending Owner’s Equity = 13,707,199.17 
  Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 13,707,199.17) / 2 = 13,353,599.585
  Net Profit = 707,199.17
  ROE = (707,199.17 / 13,353,599.585) × 100 ≈ 5.30%

2. Debt to Asset Ratio:
• First, determine total liabilities. Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity.
  Total Assets (end) = 15,200,446.16 
  Total Owner’s Equity (end) = 13,707,199.17
  Total Liabilities = 15,200,446.16 – 13,707,199.17 = 1,493,246.99
  Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets = 1,493,246.99 / 15,200,446.16 ≈ 0.0983, which we can round to 0.10

3. Gross Profit Margin:
• This is calculated by dividing Gross Profit by Total Revenue.
  Gross Profit = 2,329,939.23 
  Total Revenue = 5,064,939.23 
  Gross Profit Margin = (2,329,939.23 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 46.00%

Thus, the final answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "5.30%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.10",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "46.00%"
  }
}
